11
December
UBA GROUP CELEBRATES 10 YEARS OF OPERATIONS IN GHANA

UBA Ghana celebrated its 10th anniversary this week. The opening of UBA Ghana in January 2005, represented UBAs ambition of being the bank for Africa and Africans.

UBA Ghana was the first step in UBAs pan-African strategy, the beginning of what has been an extraordinary journey, with UBA now present in 19 African counties, as well as New York, Paris and London. This significant anniversary was marked by a series of events in Accra, Ghana, that highlighted UBAs commitment to providing superlative financial solutions and services, championing clients large and small and giving back to the wider community.

The Board of Directors of UBA group for the first time in the Banks history, chose Accra as the location for a board meeting. Matters on the Boards agenda included the continued development and expansion of the Groups activities both in Africa and globally. The choice of Ghana as the location for these pivotal talks, illustrated UBAs ongoing commitment to its Pan-African agenda. Although, proud of the Banks Nigerian heritage, UBAs ambition is pan-African, an agent to shape Africas destiny, helping increase trade, break down barriers and fund growth.

According to the Chairman of UBA plc, Mr. Tony Elumelu, as he spoke to the Ghanaian audience during the anniversary celebrations We do banking the way we do, because we want to unite Africa to the world.

Mr Elumelu along with a delegation of UBA Ghana and UBA group board members also had the privilege of an audience with President John Mahama of the Republic of Ghana. Discussions focused on exploring ways in which UBA could effectively partner with Ghanaian government, in its aims to create a dynamic nation, which cements its position as an economic power house in Africa.

The Board also attended the Accra Academy, for the Read Africa Event. Read Africa is a pioneering initiative, run by the UBA Foundation, that seeks to encourage young people to read widely and in particular authors from the African continent. The Accra event was graced with the presence of the celebrated author, Ama Ata Aidoo, who read excerpts from her book The Girl Who Can, together with UBAs Executive Director of Resources, Obi Ibekwe. The event which was attended by school children from Accra Academy and Accra Wesley Girls High School, saw the young children being inspired by the speeches they listened to, as they each received a copy of the book, courtesy of UBA Foundation. The programme highlighted the importance of life-long learning and cultivating a habit of seeking knowledge.

The celebrations concluded with UBA Ghana holding a Black Tie Gala at the newly opened Kempinski Hotel in Accra. In attendance were Ghanas financial and business elites, including the Governor of the Central Bank of Ghana, as well as the Board of Directors of both UBA group and UBA Ghana, and the banks most loyal customers and longstanding staff members. The evenings theme of a decade of achievements was illustrated evocatively through poetry, music and dance. As the Chairman of the Board, Mr Tony Elumelu CON, succinctly stated; this was a thank you for a job well done. It has been a privilege to serve you for the last ten years and all of us at UBA look forward to serving you for many years to come.

A special Citation was awarded to Dr Awele Elumelu, a pioneer board member of UBA Ghana. Other pioneer staff were also acknowledged for their long term of service to UBA customers.

Looking forward to the future, UBA Ghana will continue in its mission of democratising banking in Ghana, supporting Ghanaian entrepreneurs, the women and men who are creating a new Africa, in growing their businesses in Ghana and beyond. UBA Ghanas 25 branches, serve over 17,000 customers, embracing the digital revolution, offering customers cashless services, whilst continuing to deliver the fundamentals of a strong customer service focus: providing timely solutions and supporting customers, big and small, in realising their financial objectives.

UBA GHANA IS 7th BEST COMPANY IN GHANA.

UBA Ghana on the 23rd of October was adjudged the 7th best company in the exclusive and prestigious multi-sectoral business grouping, the Ghana club 100 (GC 100) 2014 editions

The Ghana club 100, spearheaded by the Ghana Investment Promotion Centre (GIPC), is an annual list of top 100 companies in Ghana.

The first list was compiled in 1998 to recognize the best companies in the different sectors of the Ghanas economy. The awards also aim at encouraging competition and improve products and services.

This 2013/2014 event, held at the Banquet Hall of the State House, was on the theme Impact Investments and Sustainable Economic Development.

23
September
UBA Foundation announces the commencement of the 2015 edition of the National Essay Competition for senior secondary school students in Ghana

L-R: DMD, Usman Isiaka; MD/CEO, UBA Foundation, Ijeoma Aso; Deputy Minister of Education in charge of Tertiary education, Samuel Okuddjeto Ablakwa; MD/CEO, UBA Ghana, Mrs. Abiola Bawuah and Director of Secondary Education Mr. Micheal Inkoom


UBA Foundation, the Cooperate Social Responsibility (CSR) arm of the United Bank for Africa (UBA) Plc, announces the commencement of the 2015 edition of the National Essay Competition for senior secondary school students in Ghana.

This years essay topic is: What matters most to you in life and why?
Prospective applicants must send in handwritten essay of not more than 750 words before the 30th of October, 2015.

Launching the competition, Deputy Minister of Education in-charge of Tertiary Education, Samuel Okudzeto Ablakwa said it was in the right direction and the Ministry will continue to support such initiatives.

He also urged other cooperate institutions to emulate UBA and support the Education sector.

He congratulated UBA and encouraged them not to backslide in their duty to supporting Ghanaian secondary school students.

According to the Managing Director of UBA, Mrs. Abiola Bawuah, though the competition started just last year,it has come to stay and in the near future the Foundation will increase the number of awardees and prizes.

The competition, which is a follow up on the Foundation's Read Africa Initiative, provides a competitive platform to develop the intellectual and writing abilities of senior secondary school students in Ghana.

Winners get educational grants to study in any African University of their choice.

The ultimate winner gets a Ghs 20,000.00, while the 1st runner -up takes home Ghs 14,000.00 for tuition fees, and the 2nd runner-up grabs Ghs 8,000.00.

All 12 finalists also each will receive a laptop to aid their education

ESSAY TOPIC:

What matters most to you in life and why?

Entry Procedures And Rules
  • Applicants should send in handwritten essay entries of not more than 750 words on the above topic to United Bank for Africa (Ghana) Ltd, Heritage Tower, Ambassadorial Enclave, Liberia Road- Ridge P.M.B. 29, Ministries-Accra, Ghana entries can also be dropped in all UBA branches across Ghana.
  • Applicants must submit their complete contact information (name & address of school, telephone number, residential and email addresses).
  • Applicants must attach photocopies of their original birth certificates or international passport data pages.
  • Entries close on October 30, 2015. Late entries will not be accepted.
  • Applicants must be senior secondary school students schooling in Ghana.
  • The educational grant is only applicable to applicants who intend to study in an African University.

06
July
UBA Ghana Holds Finacle 10x Training

In a bid to improve the day-to-day operations and provide excellent customer service in UBA banking halls, UBA Ghana has held a 3-day intensive training on the new Finacle 10x application at the Madina Training Centre for selected user groups.

The MD/CEO of UBA Ghana, Mrs. Abiola Bawuah expressed her appreciation to the facilitators for organizing the training and challenged staff to leverage the training opportunity to improve their knowledge.

Head, UBA Academy Group 1, Mr. Abayomi Orungbe, in his address, gave a broad overview of the new application to the participants and advised them to seriously focus on the training, which will help UBA Ghana to improve service delivery.

Chief Operations Officer, UBA Ghana, Mr. Adedayo Adesipo, reiterated the banks commitment to democratize banking in Ghana, saying that the training was in line with this strategic thrust.

The training was organized as part of the processes put in place for the smooth transition to a new Finacle 10x platform to enhance the day to day operational activities of the UBA Group.

16
June
MD/CEO, UBA Ghana Participates in Ghana Economic Forum

The MD/CEO, UBA Ghana, Mrs. Abiola Bawuah on Wednesday, June 10, 2015 joined other MDs, top government officials and experts in the industry at this years Ghana Economic Forum held at the Movenpick Ambassador Hotel.

The Ghana Economic Forum is a private-sector led initiative by Business & Financial Times newspaper which seeks to create the platform to debate and propose viable solutions for the numerous challenges that confronts the Ghanaian Economy.

This years forum, which focused on the theme:Ghanaian-Owned Economy: Setting the Agenda for Achieving Itwas opened by the Vice President of the Republic of Ghana, His Excellency, Paa Kwasi Amissah Arthur who admonished banks operating in Ghana to invest more into the real sector of the economy.

Mrs. Abiola Bawuah, who was a panelist at the discussion on Debt Financing in Ghana, admonished government to ensure monies borrowed are channeled into infrastructure projects under a Public-Private partnership framework. She advised government to limit borrowing for recurrent expenditure and rather focus more on projects that are self-sustaining.

At the end of the two day forum, a communique was put together to be presented to government and relevant agencies for consideration and implementation.

06
January
RENEWED OUTLOOK FOR 2015

UBA Ghana on friday January 2, 2015 outdoored a new corporate attire for its front office operations staff in all of its banking halls across the country.

Explaining the rationale behind this, the MD/CEO Mrs. Abiola Bawuah indicated that the bank decided to outdoor this new attire on this first working day of the year to symbolize the banks new commitment for service delivery. At UBA, we pay close attention to service quality hence the need to go a step further in grooming the staff who on daily basis interact with our customers. It is our believe that the energy and confidence the corporate attire has generated already will impact the excellent customer service delivery disposition for 2015 she concluded.

The Chief Operations Officer Mr. Adedayo Adesipo in a message to the front office staff advised them to ensure that customer experience on the shop floors become a point of reference in the industry. The Operations staff in a short interaction with the reporter expressed their appreciation to the bank for adorning them with a new corporate attire which strongly elicits the UBA brand personality of energy, boldness and confidence .
